		<title>Marketing, mission, movement</title>
		<link>http://www.manton.org/2015/08/marketing-mission-movement.html</link>
		<comments>http://www.manton.org/2015/08/marketing-mission-movement.html#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Fri, 21 Aug 2015 14:10:33 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[manton]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Business]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[blogging]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[community]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[marketing]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[snippets]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.manton.org/?p=2966</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[As I was writing some documentation this week, I kept thinking about what makes great marketing copy. 37signals used to say that copywriting is a form of user interface design. That&#8217;s true but I think there&#8217;s more to it. The best products don&#8217;t just have marketing copy; they have a mission statement. They don&#8217;t just [&#8230;]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>As I was writing <a href="http://www.manton.org/2015/08/2959.html">some documentation</a> this week, I kept thinking about what makes great marketing copy. 37signals used to say that <a href="https://gettingreal.37signals.com/ch09_Copywriting_is_Interface_Design.php">copywriting is a form of user interface design</a>. That&#8217;s true but I think there&#8217;s more to it.</p>
<p>The best products don&#8217;t just have marketing copy; they have a mission statement. They don&#8217;t just sell a tool; they sell a movement.</p>
<p>When I stare at my product wondering if it&#8217;s too confusing — if it&#8217;s too different, and tries to do too many things, to be immediately understood by new users — I try to remind myself that it&#8217;s an opportunity. Instead of simply explaining what I&#8217;m doing, how can I pitch it in a way that strengthens a community around the idea. Because dozens of bloggers can spread the idea more quickly and in a more meaningful way than I can by myself.</p>
<p>And unlike a one-way press release, a community is inherently two-way. Every mention of the idea is both marketing <em>and</em> feedback. Someone blogs about how they&#8217;re excited for the product, but also how they wish it had a certain missing feature. Someone in the press writes a review, but also with a pros and cons list.</p>
<p>This cycle means the product gets better. And if we&#8217;re thoughtful in that first approach to marketing copy, then every blog post, review, and tweet that follows is laced with a little part of our mission statement.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
